<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><b><font style="font-size: 18px;">Setting up the Linux system</font></b></div><div><br /></div><div>Remove linux "linux_base-c6” if you already installed</div><div> =&gt;<font color="#ff2f92"> sudo</font> <b>pkg remove</b><font color="#ff2600"> linux_base-c6</font></div><div> # Install ""linux_base-c7” </div><div>  =&gt; cd <font color="#941100">/usr/ports/emulators/linux_base-c7</font></div><div><span>  <span><span>=&gt; sudo make install clean</span></span></span><br /></div><div><span>           <font color="#929292"> <i>—————— Message </i></font></span><font color="#929292"><i>————————</i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><span><span><span>            Some programs need linprocfs mounted on /compat/linux/proc.  Add the</span></span></span>following line </i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i>             to /etc/fstab:</i></font></div><div><font style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);"><i><span>    <span>    <span>    <span>    </span></span></span></span>linprocfs   /compat/linux/proc    linprocfs    rw    0    0<br /></i></font></div><div><i><span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);">            =&gt; sudo mount /compat/linux/proc".</span><br /></i></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><br /></i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><span>    <span>    <span>    <span> </span></span></span></span>Some programs need linsysfs mounted on /compat/linux/sys.  Add the</i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><span>    <span>    <span>    <span> </span></span></span></span>following line to /etc/fstab:</i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><span>    <span>    <span>    <span>    </span></span></span></span>linsysfs    /compat/linux/sys    linsysfs    rw    0    0</i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i>             =&gt; sudo mount /compat/linux/sys<br /></i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><br /></i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><span>    <span>    <span>    <span> The Sublime 3</span></span></span></span> needs tmpfs mounted on /compat/linux/dev/shm.  Add the</i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i>             following line to /etc/fstab:</i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><span>    <span>    <span>    <span>    </span></span></span></span>tmpfs    /compat/linux/dev/shm    tmpfs    rw,mode=1777    0    0<br /></i></font></div><div><font color="#929292"><i><span>    <span>    <span>    <span>  =&gt; sudo </span></span></span></span>mount /compat/linux/dev/shm<br /></i></font></div><div><span><i><font color="#929292">    </font><span><font color="#929292">    <span>    ——————————————————————— </span></font></span></i></span><br /></div><div><span># Edit “<font color="#941100">/etc/rc.conf</font>” and make sure that the Linux support is enabled:</span></div><div><font color="#9437ff">linux_enable</font>="<font color="#009051">YES</font>"</div><div># Now you can reboot or manually the Linux modules “<font color="#0433ff">linux.ko</font>” and “<font color="#0433ff">linux64.ko</font>”</div><div><span># I believe the “<font color="#0433ff">linux64.ko</font>” will be automatically loaded if you are running 64bits system.</span></div><div><span><span><br /></span></span></div><div><span><span><br /></span></span></div><div><span><span># Make sure that you load the “linprocfs” before trying to mount :</span></span></div><div>=&gt; <font color="#ff2f92">sudo</font> <b>kldload</b><font color="#005493"> linprocfs</font></div><div><span><span>            </span></span></div><div><span># Enable the module in the “<font color="#941100">/boot/loader.conf</font>” file:</span></div><div> <font color="#9437ff">linprocfs_load</font>=“<font color="#009051">YES</font>"</div><div><span> # Indeed enable the linux in <font color="#941100">/etc/rc.conf</font></span>”</div><div><font color="#9437ff"> linux_enable</font>=“<font color="#009051">YES</font>"</div><div><span><span><br /></span></span></div><div><span><span># Note: The mounting to "/compat/linux/dev/shm” no longer work!            </span></span></div><div><span><span># Instead create “/tmpfs” folder and mount “tmpfs” there.</span></span></div><div><span><span>=&gt; sudo mkdir /tmpfs</span></span></div><div><span><span><br /></span></span></div><div><span> # Your “<font color="#941100">/etc/fstab</font>” should look like this:</span></div><div><span><span>         </span></span>            ...</div><div><span>          <font color="#929292"> # Linux staff add:</font></span></div><div><span>    <span>    <span>    </span></span></span><font color="#941100">linprocfs</font>    <font color="#0433ff">/compat/linux/proc</font>  <font color="#009051">  linprocfs</font>    rw    0    0</div><div><span>    <span>       <font color="#941100"> </font></span></span><font color="#941100">linsysfs</font>   <font color="#0433ff"> /compat/linux/sys</font>   <font color="#009051"> linsysfs </font>   rw    0    0</div><div><span>    <span>    <span>    </span></span></span><font color="#929292"># For Sublime you definitly need this:</font></div><div><span><span></span></span><span>    <span>    <span>    </span></span></span><font color="#941100">tmpfs</font>    <font color="#0433ff">  /tmpfs</font>   <font color="#009051">  tmpfs</font>  rw,mode=1777    0       0</div><div>            <font color="#929292">### The end of “/etc/fstab”###</font></div><div><br /></div><div>IMPORTANT: You must have the “tmpfs” mounted to make the Sublime 3 to work!</div><div><br /></div><div><b><font style="font-size: 18px;">Installing the Sublime 3</font></b></div><div><b><font style="font-size: 18px;"><br /></font></b></div><div>=&gt;<b> cd</b> <font color="#941100">/usr/ports/editors/linux-sublime3</font></div><div>=&gt; <font color="#ff2f92">sudo</font> <b>make install clean</b></div><div><br /></div><div><br /></div><div><br /></div><div><span><span><br /></span></span></div><div><span><span><br /></span></span></div><div><span><span><br /></span></span></div></en-note>